From: PS4 Linux Baikal Port <noreply@ps4-linux>
Subject: [PATCH] amdgpu: v47 - floor dp_clock=270000 on Liverpool/Gladius in adjust_pll

The v46 ATOM trace (patch 0021) caught the proximate cause of the dark
screen at log line 2625:

  ps4_atom: AdjustDisplayPll v1.3 IN pix=0 tx=0x1e enc=0 cfg=0x20 ext_tx=0x00 dp_clock=0
  ps4_atom: AdjustDisplayPll v1.3 OUT r=0 freq=0 ref=0 post=0

dp_clock=0 is the input. The encoder runs in DP mode (enc=0 =
ATOM_ENCODER_MODE_DP), and the v3 case branch sets

  args.v3.sInput.usPixelClock = cpu_to_le16(dp_clock / 10);

so feeding zero in produces zero out. ATOM executes cleanly (r=0), no
abort, and dutifully writes ulDispPllFreq=0 because that's what zero
input deserves.

The reason dp_clock is zero: amdgpu_atombios_crtc_adjust_pll reads it
from dig_connector->dp_clock at line 332. On Liverpool/Gladius that
field is never populated. Patch 0001 wires connector .detect to
ps4_bridge_detect, but our boot path force-attaches the bridge at probe
(patch 0007 -> pre_enable + enable + mode_set), bypassing detect. The
DPCD-read path that would normally fill in dp_clock never runs, so
dig_connector->dp_clock stays at its zero-init value through the entire
mode_set.

v46 attempted to fix this by writing dp_clock=270000 inside
ps4_bridge_detect, but that callback never runs in our path either.
v46 boot log shows zero hits for the "ps4_bridge_detect: forcing
dp_clock=270000" marker. The defensive write was placed in the wrong
function.

This patch (v47) moves the fix to the actual consumer. Right after the
existing dp_clock = dig_connector->dp_clock line in
amdgpu_atombios_crtc_adjust_pll, gate on Liverpool/Gladius and floor
dp_clock to 270000 if it's still zero. PS4's internal GPU->MN864729
DisplayPort link is hardwired at 4 lanes @ 2.7 Gbps regardless of the
EDID/DPCD read outcome, so 270000 kHz is the correct value.

The v46 trace patch (0021) stays in place as ongoing visibility.

Expected v47 trace on next boot:

  ps4_atom: flooring dp_clock 0 -> 270000 (PS4 internal DP link)
  ps4_atom: AdjustDisplayPll v1.3 IN pix=27000 tx=0x1e enc=0 cfg=0x20 ext_tx=0x00 dp_clock=270000
  ps4_atom: AdjustDisplayPll v1.3 OUT r=0 freq=<non-zero> ref=<N> post=<N>

If freq comes back non-zero with valid divider hints, the v28 fallback
path no longer fires, amdgpu_pll_compute receives real ATOM output, and
the bridge cq_wait_set 3-second hang at log line 2645 should shrink to
<500ms (lane lock acquired). HDMI lights up.

If freq still returns 0 with non-zero input, the DP-mode AdjustDisplayPll
branch on Liverpool needs more than just a non-zero pixel clock — likely
ucDispPllConfig or ucExtTransmitterID also need PS4-specific values. The
v46 trace already shows: tx=0x1e enc=0 cfg=0x20 ext_tx=0x00 — those
fields become the next investigation.

---
--- a/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/atombios_crtc.c
+++ b/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/atombios_crtc.c
@@ -333,6 +333,20 @@
 		}
 	}

+	/* v47 (PS4 Liverpool/Gladius): the connector detect/dpcd path doesn't
+	 * run in our boot flow (bridge is force-attached at probe by patch
+	 * 0007), so dig_connector->dp_clock stays at its zero-init value.
+	 * That zeroes args.v3.sInput.usPixelClock when ENCODER_MODE_IS_DP,
+	 * which makes ATOM AdjustDisplayPll return ulDispPllFreq=0 (GIGO,
+	 * confirmed by v46 trace: pix=0 dp_clock=0 -> OUT freq=0 ref=0 post=0).
+	 * Floor it here to the PS4-internal DP link rate (4 lanes @ 2.7 Gbps =
+	 * 270000 kHz) so ATOM gets a sane input. */
+	if ((adev->asic_type == CHIP_LIVERPOOL || adev->asic_type == CHIP_GLADIUS)
+	    && dp_clock == 0) {
+		pr_info("ps4_atom: flooring dp_clock 0 -> 270000 (PS4 internal DP link)\n");
+		dp_clock = 270000;
+	}
+
 	/* use recommended ref_div for ss */
 	if (amdgpu_encoder->devices & (ATOM_DEVICE_LCD_SUPPORT)) {
 		if (amdgpu_crtc->ss_enabled) {
